<div class="text-center p-4">
  <h2>Reusing Components</h2>
  <p class="lead">Keeping it DRY</p>
</div>

@if (ViewBag.IsComplete == false)
{
  @using (Html.BeginForm())
  {
<div class="row justify-content-center">
  <div class="text-center container-sm col-8 col-sm-6 rounded">
    <div class="text center col-12">
    @using (Html.BeginForm())
    {
      <input type="submit" value= "Mark Complete" class = "bn632-hover bn20" />
    }
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
  }
} else if (ViewBag.IsComplete == true)
{
<div class="row justify-content-center">
  <div class="text-center container-sm col-8 col-sm-6 rounded">
    <div class="text center col-12">
    @using (Html.BeginForm())
    {
      <input type="submit" value= "Completed" class = "bn632-hover bn22" />
    }
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
}

<section class="text-content p-3 m-3">
  <div class="container-md p-3 m-3">
    <p class="lead">  
      Throughout your coding journey you've probably been told the importance of making code reusable. This is no different in React. No one wants to keep writing similar code when they don't have to, and companies don't want to foot the bill for their programmers to repeat themselves if it's not necessary. LogRocket has a <a href="https://blog.logrocket.com/building-reusable-ui-components-with-react-hooks/">Building Reusable UI Components</a> tutorial where they say:

      <blockquote class="px-5 p-3 px-3 mx-5 p-3 border border-light">This pattern of creating React components is necessary for scaling. It helps save time by ensuring less code is written, development is faster, the codebase is simpler, and maintenance is stress-free.</blockquote>
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      <a href="https://blog.bitsrc.io/reusable-components-in-react-a-practical-guide-ec15a81a4d71">Another tutorial</a> on the subject from blog.bitsrc.io goes through some of the best practices for building reusable React components. 
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      There's a video tutorial and more links just for you if you look downtown. 
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

